"Martínez-Meyer E., Peterson A.T., Servín J.I., Kiff L.F.","Ecological niche modelling and prioritizing areas for species reintroductions",2006,"ORYX","40","4",,"411","418",,,10.1017/S0030605306001360,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33846056901&partnerID=40&md5=f41043461ac578fd96cbda39ee70b24a","Departamento de Zoología, Instituto de Biología, Ciudad Universitaria, Circuito Exterior s/n, Mexico City 04510, Mexico; Natural History Museum, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Departamento de Desarrollo Sustentable, Instituto de Ciencias Sociales, Universidad Juárez del Estado de Durango, Apdo. Postal 123, Durango 34001, Mexico; Peregrine Fund, 5668 West Flying Hawk Lane, Boise, ID 83709, United States","Martínez-Meyer, E., Departamento de Zoología, Instituto de Biología, Ciudad Universitaria, Circuito Exterior s/n, Mexico City 04510, Mexico; Peterson, A.T., Natural History Museum, University of Kansas, Lawrence, KS 66045, United States; Servín, J.I., Departamento de Desarrollo Sustentable, Instituto de Ciencias Sociales, Universidad Juárez del Estado de Durango, Apdo. Postal 123, Durango 34001, Mexico; Kiff, L.F., Peregrine Fund, 5668 West Flying Hawk Lane, Boise, ID 83709, United States","Species reintroduction programmes, in prioritizing areas for reintroductions, have traditionally used tools that include measures of habitat suitability and evaluations of area requirements for viable populations. Here we add two tools to this approach: evaluation of ecological requirements of species and evaluation of future suitability for species facing changing climates. We demonstrate this approach with two species for which reintroduction programmes are in the planning stages in Mexico: California condor Gymnogyps californianus and Mexican wolf Canis lupus baileyi. For the condor, we identify three areas clustered in the Sierra San Pedro Mártir, Baja California; for the wolf, we identify a string of suitable sites along the Sierra Madre Occidental of western Mexico. We discuss the limitations of this approach, identifying ways in which the models illustrated could be made more realistic and directly useful to reintroduction programmes. © 2006 FFI.","California condor; Canis lupus baileyi; Ecological niche modelling; Gymnogyps californianus; Mexican wolf; Reintroduction","canid; conservation planning; ecological modeling; habitat selection; niche; reintroduction; Baja California [(STT) Mexico]; Mexico [North America]; North America; Sierra Madre; Sierra Madre Occidental; Sierra San Pedro Martir National Park; Canis familiaris; Canis lupus baileyi; Gymnogyps californianus",,,,,,"Anderson, R.P., Gómez-Laverde, M., Peterson, A.T., Geographical distributions of spiny pocket mice in South America: Insights from predictive models (2002) Global Ecology and Biogeography, 11, pp. 131-141; Anderson, R.P., Lew, D., Peterson, A.T., Evaluating predictive models of species' distributions: Criteria for selecting optimal models (2003) Ecological Modelling, 162, pp. 211-232; Austin, M.P., Nicholls, A.O., Margules, C.R., Measurement of the realized qualitative niche: Environmental niches of five Eucalyptus species (1990) Ecological Monographs, 60, pp. 161-177; Bright, P.W., Smithson, T.J., Biological invasions provide a framework for reintroductions: Selecting areas in England for pine marten releases (2001) Biodiversity and Conservation, 10, pp. 1247-1265; Carey, P.D., Brown, N.J., The use of GIS to identify sites that will become suitable for a rare orchid, Himantoglossum hircinum L., in a future changed climate (1994) Biodiversity Letters, 2, pp. 117-123; Carpenter, G., Gillison, A.N., Winter, J., DOMAIN: A flexible modeling procedure for mapping potential distributions of animals and plants (1993) Biodiversity and Conservation, 2, pp. 667-680; Carson, D.J., Climate modelling: Achievements and prospects (1999) Quarterly Journal of the Royal Meteorological Society, 125, pp. 1-27; Cramer, P.C., Portier, K.M., Modeli